<FIRST>u i AM-Egypt-Jordan     08-27 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Jordan,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Egypt and Jordan Call For Syria To Cooperate With Arab League</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egypt and Jordan on Sunday urged Syria to
cooperate with an Arab league committee appointed to mediate an end
to conflict in Lebanon that has left nearly 800 people in less than
six months.
   King Hussein of Jordan met with Egypt's President Hosni Mubarak
in Cairo for three hours of talks on regional issues, principally
the escalating violence in Lebanon between Christian troops and
Syrian-backed Moslems.
   The latest round in the conflict broke out in March when
Christian army commander, Gen. Michel Aoun, blockaded illegal
Moslem-run ports. The Syrians responded by blockading the
310-square-mile Christian enclave.
   Mubarak said he hoped ``Syria would cooperate with'' a
three-member Arab League committee of Algeria, Morocco and Saudi
Arabia appointed in a May Arab summit in Casablanca, Morocco to
mediate peace in Lebanon.
   ``Must not leave the solution for what is happening in Lebanon to
non-Arab countries, because that would make us appear weak,''
Mubarak told reporters after the meeting. ``We as Arabs are
responsible for what happens in Lebanon.''
   Mubarak apparently referred to French and Soviet negotiations
last week with Christian and Moslem leaders in Lebanon and Syria.
The Soviet Union is Syria's principal weapons supplier.
   Hussein said, however, it was uncertain whether the Arab League
committee will be able to carry out its mandate to end to the war.
The committee said this month that its efforts had failed and blamed
Syria for refusing to schedule withdrawal of its estaimted 40,000
troops from Lebanon.
   ``We must wait and see whether the committee will continue its
work or not,'' Hussein said.
   Syria entered Lebanon with a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping
mandate but became involved on the Moslem side of that country's
civil war.
   A Jordanian official said in Amman on condition of anonymity,
that Jordan, Egypt and other Arab countries were mediating with the
Syrians to end Lebanon's violence.
   On Saturday, Hussein met with Syria's foreign minister, Farouk
el-Sharaa, in Amman.
   Egypt and Syria have no diplomatic ties, but relations have
improved recently after 10 years of bitterness that followed Cairo's
peace treaty with Israel.
</TEXT>
