<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-89 1158EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Fitzgerald-Families     08-27 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fitzgerald-Families,0771</SECOND>
<HEAD>Underwater Pictures Bring Memories To `Wives And The Sons And The
Daughters'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAIGE St. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A macabre drama unfolded for a small
fellowship who, with horror and fascination, watched television film
clips of the first clear pictures of the wreck of the Edmund
Fitzgerald.
   ``Oh yes, I've watched it. I can't not watch it,'' said Ruth
Hudson, whose only child, Bruce, 22, died aboard the steel freighter
during a fierce storm Nov. 10, 1975. His body and those of 28 other
crewmen remain at the bottom of Lake Superior.
   For three days last week, explorers using a submersible robot
penetrated the cold, deep water that has cloaked and preserved the
Fitzgerald since its sinking. Their video images will provide data
on the wreck as well as the technology to study other underwater
sites.
   For the families of the Fitzgerald crew, the expedition opened
wounds.
   ``People say it gets easier. Naturally, it's eased some. But to
me it was just yesterday,'' said Hudson, of North Olmstead, Ohio.
   Startling footage of the 556-foot-deep wreck _ funded by the
Great Lakes Shipwreck Historical Society _ was difficult for Hudson
to watch.
   ``It's a hard time for me. It brings back all of the panic,'' she
said. ``But I can't say I don't want them to do it. I have a lot of
friends that are really angry. They ask, `Why are they doing that to
the families?' But this is history. My son would have wanted it
shown.''
   She feels good about public fascination with the wreck. ``They
really haven't forgotten,'' she said.
   The tragedy became American folklore, particularly after Canadian
balladeer Gordon Lightfoot wrote a hit song in 1976 about the death
of the boat he called ``the pride of the American side.''
   ``All that remains is the faces and the names of the wives and
the sons and the daughters,'' he sang.
   Edmund Bacon Fitzgerald said by telephone from Tennessee last
week that his father, the Edmund Fitzgerald for whom the the
freighter was named, was haunted by the wreck until his death in
1986. The father was president of Northwestern Mutual Life Insurance
Co., which built the ship in 1958.
   The Edmund Fitzgerald left Superior, Wis., under threatening
skies Nov. 9 on what was to have been its last trip down the Great
Lakes before docking for the winter.
   By the next day, the Fitzgerald was in a gale. Capt. Ernest
McSorley reported topside damage and a list to his boat as 30-foot
waves crashed over the freighter.
   Just 15 miles short of the protection of Whitefish Bay, McSorley
spoke by ship's radio to the Arthur M. Anderson, another freighter
struggling through the storm. Although the beacon light that marked
the entrance to the bay had gone out, both skippers were sure they'd
make it.
   ``We are holding our own,'' McSorley told the Anderson's crew.
   Shortly afterward, the Fitzgerald disappeared from radar screens
without even a distress call. No bodies and very little wreckage was
found.
   There are conflicting theories on how the Fitzgerald sank _
whether water entered its hold through leaking hatch covers or it
hit a shoal. Underwater divers later found that the ship went down
with such force it broke in two.
   The search robot's first images Wednesday were of a stark white
bow rising crumpled and torn out of the blackness. Researchers were
struck not by the damage but by the incongruity of a gleaming water
cooler surrounded by overturned equipment in the pilothouse.
   Bill Peckol of Ashtabula, Ohio, is eager to see the footage being
filmed for a National Geographic Society television show. He's
already seen the snippets on newscasts.
   ``Naturally, they're not going to change anything that has
happened,'' said Peckol, whose 20-year-old son, Karl, died on the
ship. ``But maybe they can shed more light on what possibly
happened.''
   Bettie Peckol remembers her relief when Karl took a job on the
Fitzgerald, transferring from a smaller and, she thought, more
dangerous boat named Sensibar.
   ``The irony of it is, the Sensibar is still sailing,'' said Mrs.
Peckol, who skipped newscasts of the wreckage. ``I'm not happy about
opening up a lot of old wounds. I guess you never forget the loss of
a child.
   ``Plus, I don't believe in living in the past. I want to remember
Karl the way he was the last time I saw him.''
   That was Nov. 7, 1975. He was waving goodbye.
</TEXT>
