<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-89 1214EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-BushParaphernalia Bjt   08-27 0837</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush Paraphernalia, Bjt,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Souvenir Business Flourishing At President's Summer Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suppose you have a craving for some
``Bush Sauce'' with your quail dinner. Or maybe you want to snuggle
your feet into a pair of American flag slippers adorned with George
and Barbara dolls. Perhaps you'd just like to pick up a ``Read my
lips'' wall clock.
   Kennebunkport is your shopping destination.
   The proliferation of Bush paraphernalia in this resort town of
nearly 3,000 people is giving tourists a variety of souvenir options
to prove _ once they get home to Quebec or Connecticut or Kansas _
that they have, indeed, been to the summer vacation home of the 41st
president.
   What kitchen, for example couldn't use a little refrigerator
magnet with a plastic Maine lobster and the words ``Kennebunkport,
Maine. Home of George W. Bush'' on it?
   Those sell for $2.50 each at the What's In Store, a curio shop
that also features mugs emblazoned with the eagle symbol of the
United States and a picture of Bush's home on Walker's Point.
   In the same shop, you can have your picture taken with a lifesize
picture of Bush for $5.
   Or how about a kid's bib that says ``I was a guest at Walker's
Point, Kennebunkport,'' or a dishtowel bearing the blue grinning
image of the president at $4.99 each?
   The president himself gave a plug Friday for a new item selling
at the Cape Arundel Golf Club shop.
   ``You want me to sell some shirts for you?'' he asked golf pro
Ken Raynor as they teed off. He turned to a group of reporters and
photographers and pointed to the insignia on his knit shirt. ``It
says D.C. and Maine. They're really nice. I'm recommending them.''
   The ``new presidential shirts'' sell for $36 in the golf shop,
where photos of Bush driving a golf cart adorn the wall.
   Back in the quaint center of town, all manner of Bush-inspired
T-shirts are hot sellers. Slogans emblazoned across shirts include
the well-worn ``KenneBushport,'' ``The Summer White House,
Kennebunkport, Maine,'' with a picture of Bush's Walker's Point
home, and ``George Bush Sleeps Here.''
   For those getting ready for Halloween, the Paper Plus toys and
curio store sells cardboard Bush masks, with cutout eyes, for $3.95.
The masks are displayed on a wall between an autographed photo of
comedian Pee Wee Herman and a photo of Joan Collins, smiling in a
white negligee and autographed with the words, ``To all my darlings
at Paper Plus. I'll always cherish this day.''
   The store also sells the ``Sleeping Partnerzzz'' slippers, at $30
a pair, which feature plastic George and Barbara Bush heads peeping
out from flag-striped slippers. Each plastic doll head rests on a
pillow, also part of the slipper, emblazoned with the eagle seal of
the United States.
   Mrs. Bush grimaced a few months back when a local restaurateur
showed her a pair of the slippers.
   The Open Door Gift Shop features Bush Sauce, created by The Hagen
House company of neargy Orgunquit, Maine, at $5.25 for a 16-ounce
jar.
   Proprietor Jody Bibber says it's so popular ``I can't keep it in.
... It's just a fun item.''
   The label says the tomato and onion relish is ``excellent with
quail'' and makes a nice garnish for chicken or fish.
   In keeping with the Bush jargon, one flavor is labelled
``kinder-gentler,'' and the label also urges the shopper to ``Shower
your taste buds with a thousand points of light.''
   Another Bush-ism inspired a $46 clock at the Argo gift shop.
   The clock is in the shape of bright red lips with a cartoon-style
balloon coming from them carrying the words ``Read my lips.''
   Proprietor Ron Joslyn said he's not really into Bush
paraphernalia but picked up two of the novelty clocks at a craft
show. He sent one to Bush via the son of a friend who cares for the
Bushes' pool. He doesn't know if the president received it.
   Irreverence is the key to some of the novelties. One version of
the Bush mask carries the caution: ``Not intended for use by
children under the age of 3 or by Dan Quayle. May cause drowsiness
while operating heavy machinery, pitching horseshoes, vetoing
legislation. ... Misuse may result in 1,000 points of light.''
   Lisa Mills, who runs a corporate and personal shopping service,
said her clients are looking for all types of more refined
Bush-oriented gifts.
   ``Everybody wants Maine products with Bush's home painted on
them,'' she said adding that a popular item has been a $35
breakfast-in-bed tray with Walker's Point on it.
   The more thrifty souvenir shopper can pick up plastic thimbles,
at $6.99 each, with Bush's picture on them, or shot glasses, $3.95
each, bearing the presidential seal and the words Kennebunkport,
Maine.
   Chamber of Commerce Chairwoman Barbara Aiello, contending that
Kennebunkport hasn't let itself be overwhelmed by tackiness,
acknowledged that some of the Bush products are ``borderline
tasteful'' and that ``expensive tacky is creeping in.''
</TEXT>
