<FIRST>u i AM-Baltics Bjt   08-27 0835</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baltics, Bjt,0859</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baltic Residents Make Bold New Push For Independence</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLINN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Independence. A year ago, only a few
former political prisoners dared whisper the word in the nation's
three Baltic republics.
   Today, it is the goal of a mass movement, putting the three tiny
lands in direct conflict with the Kremlin.
   On Wednesday, a 370-mile chain of determined Baltic families
stood hand in hand, protesting the Soviet annexation of their
independent nations. But that was just the most dramatic
manifestation of a profound change that has occurred in recent
months on the Soviet Union's western frontier.
   The activist groups of Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania, known as
the People's Front, once worked for more authority within the Soviet
Union. Now, they are openly calling for restoration of their free
nations.
   ``The declarations of the People's Front in the past year have
become ever closer to the ideals our people have carried in their
hearts for all these 50 years,'' Estonian People's Front leader and
lawmaker Marju Lauristin said.
   ``All of us would like to have freedom, and freedom without
independence isn't realistic,'' she said.
   From the Kremlin's point of view, it is Baltic independence
that's unrealistic, and a sharply worded statement from the
Communist Party Central Committee on Saturday made that point clear.
   ``Things have gone far. Serious danger is threatening the Baltic
peoples,'' the policy-making body said. ``People should know what
abyss their nationalist leaders are pushing them toward.''
   ``If they managed to attain their goals, the consequences could
be catastrophic for their people. Their very ability to survive
could come under question,'' it said. The statement was carried on
national television.
   Not long ago, such a warning from the Central Committee would
have sent shudders through many activists. On Sunday, it did little
more than raise eyebrows in the Baltics _ yet another indication of
how far the region has come in establishing for itself an identity
outside the Soviet Union.
   ``We expected this,'' said Raimona Sakalouskis, a spokeswoman for
the Lithuanian activist group. But leaders of the People's Front
movements didn't interrupt their weekend plans to discuss the
statement.
   The radicalization of the fronts is backed by more than 2 million
people who signed documents implying they want freedom from the
Soviet Union.
   In Lithuania, 1.3 million people have signed petitions saying the
Soviet Union annexed their nation ``against the will of
Lithuanians.'' It demands removal of the Soviet ``occupation army''
and seeks U.N. supervision of free elections for a new Baltic
government.
   In Latvia, 430,000 people have registered themselves as desiring
to be considered citizens of an independent Latvia.
   In Estonia, more than 400,000 have signed petitions asking the
Estonian parliament to declare illegal the 1940 Estonian
parliament's approval of the Soviet annexation. That legislature was
elected under Soviet occupation and only Communists were allowed to
run.
   For the Kremlin, the Baltics are front-line territory, home to
missile bases, naval and army units, and vital ports. Activists say
one in eight people in Estonia is a Soviet soldier.
   Soviet television called the idea of redrawing boundaries
``political naivete'' in its coverage of Wednesday's protest.
   ``Independence _ it'll never happen,'' said a Tallinn taxi
driver, the son of a Russian-Estonian marriage. The economy is a
wreck and hopes of developing a new tourist industry fail to take
into consideration the cold, damp Baltic climate, he said.
   Significant opposition to independence also has come from the 2.7
million Russians and other non-Baltic people among the 8 million
Baltic residents.
   Yet amid the pride and determination exhibited by the tens of
thousands of Estonians holding hands on the crest of Tallinn's
Toompea Hill on Wednesday evening, independence seemed possible.
   In the past year, the Baltics have waged a parliamentary and
legal struggle, taking full advantage of each step toward democracy
permitted by the Kremlin. Each move has run into condemnation in
Moscow, giving way to grudging acceptance, and a new push by the
Baltics.
   Estonia made international headlines in November when it claimed
the right to overturn Soviet laws. The Kremlin declared the move
invalid, but Estonia has not backed down.
   A plan for economic autonomy greeted with derision two years ago
has been approved in principle by the new Soviet legislature. Recent
strikes by Russians in Estonia over a voter residency law disturbed
activists, but the Kremlin refrained from issuing orders and strove
for a peaceful compromise.
   Alvydas Medalinskas, a leader of the Lithuanian activist group
Sajudis, said it would not now exist if it had spoken of
independence even in January.
   On Wednesday, the Sajudis council pushed again. It voted to call
for ``creation of an independent democratic Lithuanian republic not
under the power of the Soviet Union.''
   A day earlier, the Lithuanian parliament passed a resolution
calling the Soviet annexation ``an international crime.''
   In Latvia, the People's Front will take a formal vote soon at its
congress on changing its platform to full independence, said
Chairman Ianis Freimanis.
</TEXT>
