<FIRST>u a AM-Church-HousingBattle Bjt   08-27 0957</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Church-Housing Battle, Bjt,910</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tenants Win Battle With Church Over HUD-Financed High-Rise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fundamentalist church group improperly
spent $117,000 earmarked for a low-income housing project here and
tried to evade government rules in order to sell the building at an
enormous profit, HUD records and court documents show.
   The sale of The Concord, a 150-unit high-rise building, was
halted through the persistence of tenants who feared they would be
evicted or their rents would triple, lawyers familiar with the case
said.
   The tenants urged the inspector general at the Department of
Housing and Urban Development to conduct an audit, which found
$117,787 in project funds were improperly spent by The Concord's
owner, Community Churches of America.
   Among other things, HUD found that Concord funds were used to pay
church group officers and purchase two vans used for church events.
The housing agency eventually reached a settlement with the group on
the misspent money.
   The Glendale-based fundamentalist group first tried to sell the
apartment building in 1982 for $5.5 million, after paying off the
balance of a $2.05 million HUD loan to the original developer.
Congress has since prohibited pre-payment of HUD loans unless the
housing secretary finds that existing tenants are protected from
eviction or higher rents.
   Community Churches tried again in 1985 to sell the building for
$5.5 million, under the protection of a bankruptcy reorganization.
But the bankruptcy sale was blocked after objections were raised by
tenants, church creditors and HUD lawyers, according to court
records on file in nearby Los Angeles.
   Community Churches was headed by the Rev. William S. McBirnie, a
charismatic preacher. Community Churches acquired The Concord in
1979 and organized a non-profit foundation to run the building in
accordance with HUD regulations. The building was erected in 1966 to
provide subsidized housing for the elderly and handicapped.
   But there were problems from the outset, said Clements Gordon,
81, a former building manager who spearheaded the tenants' fight.
   McBirnie planned to use the Concord to house his own parishioners
and the loyal listeners to his anti-communist radio broadcasts,
``Voice of Americanism,'' she said.
   By 1982, McBirnie decided to sell The Concord because ``we were
constantly being frustrated at making improvements in the building
and not being able to do the good work that we had intended,'' he
said in a legal declaration. He did not return a reporter's
telephone call seeking comment.
   HUD's ``decision to allow the prepayment was very suspect,'' said
Ben Logan, a Los Angeles lawyer representing the building's tenants.
After the HUD loan was repaid, the agency lost its regulatory
control over the building.
   Even the church's lawyer, Philip McNutt, acknowledged, ``The idea
of HUD authorizing this prepayment for the benefit of a private
owner was a real political hot potato at the time.''
   Tenants asked HUD about the legality of the sale, and were told
HUD regulations did not prohibit Community Churches group from
paying off its loan early, Mrs. Gordon said.
   Of course, HUD ``was concerned over the impact upon existing
tenants,'' HUD Deputy Assistant Secretary Philip Abrams wrote Mrs.
Gordon in July 1982. ``We insisted upon an agreement by the project
owners that all existing tenants would have the opportunity to
remain in occupancy without interference by the (new) owner until
such time as they may freely choose to leave.''
   But in testimony about a week later before the House Select
Committee on Aging, Abrams conceded the sale was authorized before
HUD received any written pledge from McBirnie's group guaranteeing
the residents' life tenancy.
   ``The primary concern of the tenants was that they were going to
be evicted or that their rents were going to be raised so high they
were going to have to leave,'' McNutt said. ``But that was never
reflected in reality.''
   In August 1982, Mrs. Gordon and other tenants filed suit to block
the sale of The Concord.
   There was intense pressure to settle because McBirnie's groups
had obtained a short-term loan at high interest to pay off the HUD
loan, McNutt said. McBirnie's groups had used the short-term loan
because they intended to sell the building immediately, but their
plan was thwarted by the tenants' lawsuit, Logan said.
   ``The deal essentially was shoved down the foundation's throat,
because it was either lose the building through foreclosure or
accept the government's offer,'' McNutt said. As a result, a 1983
settlement was reached that included a new $2.6 million HUD loan on
the building and again HUD-imposed rules on its operations.
   New trouble surfaced in May 1985 when a Los Angeles County
Superior Court issued a $1.28 million default judgment against
McBirnie's church groups in a suit that alleged 26 people were
defrauded after investing about $200,000 in loans for new church
facilities. Eventually, 380 creditors filed lawsuits claiming they
were owed as much as $3.7 million.
   The next month, Community Churches filed for bankruptcy
reorganization in Washington, D.C., eventually listing The Concord
as a major asset. In the bankruptcy proceeding, McNutt proposed to
satisfy creditors by selling The Concord to the same buyer lined up
in the 1982 deal.
   The resurrected sale of The Concord in bankruptcy court ``was
just a transparent attempt to do in bankruptcy court what the civil
suits and the congressional hearings had prevented earlier,'' Logan
said.
   After the case was transferred to Los Angeles, the bankruptcy
court appointed an independent trustee to supervise the
reorganization.
   Three more years of legal maneuvering ended July 31 with a deal
that closed the sale of The Concord for $1.35 million and assumption
of the $2.2 million remaining on the HUD loan.
   The new owner, the Retirement Housing Foundation, has pledged to
operate the building according to HUD regulations.
</TEXT>
