<HEAD>Eds: SUBS DERRY, N.H.-dated d4th item to CORRECT in 2nd graf that
Shepard was first U.S. man in space, sted first man in space. ADDS 2 grafs
on end with background.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DERRY, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former astronaut Alan B. Shepard was the big
draw at an auction of his boyhood home.
   ``It's a happy day,'' said the man who made the first U.S. flight
into space in 1961, as he autographed the backs of pictures and seat
panels of chairs for winning bidders Saturday.
   Someone paid $160,000 for the house, where Shepard has not lived
since he entered the U.S. Naval Academy in 1944.
   Shepard, who now lives in Texas, said his mother has purchased a
smaller home near his sister in North Carolina.
   As one of the United States' first group of astronauts, Shepard
made a 15-minute suborbital flight on May 5, 1961, becoming the
first American in space. The previous month, Yuri Gagarin of the
Soviet Union became the first man in space when he orbited the earth.
   In 1971, Shepard was the fifth person to walk on the moon.
