<FIRST>r i AM-Austria-Refugees     08-27 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Austria-Refugees,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Austrian Authorities Say 180 More East Germans Crossed from Hungary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Austrian officials on Sunday said about
180 East Germans had crossed the Hungarian border in a 24-hour
period, despite increased attempts by Hungarian officials to stop
them.
   In Hamburg, West Germany's Welt am Sonntag newspaper reported
that Hungarian officials told their West German counterparts that
there was rising Soviet and East German concern about the stream of
East Germans fleeing through Hungary.
   Bonn officials, meanwhile, told West German radio that Hungary
had repeated assurances that no East German now in Hungary would be
sent back against his will.
   Austrian police officials in Eisenstadt, about 10 miles north of
the border, said that new refugees were arriving despite Hungarian
attempts to keep cars with East German license plates away from the
boundary, the Austrian Press Agency reported. The officials were
quoted as saying about 180 had crossed since Saturday.
   All East German cars approaching Nagycenk, two miles east of the
border and 20 miles south of Eisenstadt, were being turned back by
police, several refugees were quoted as saying.
   East Germans frustrated with the lack of domestic political or
economic reforms and unable to emigrate legally to the West began
fleeing through Hungary into Austria early this summer. Their final
goal is West Germany, which considers them citizens.
   The border between Hungary and Austria is relatively easy to
cross. Hungary, a reform-minded Soviet bloc country, removed barbed
wire and other barriers from the border in April in a symbolic
opening to the West.
   Because Hungary is an allied Communist country, East Germans can
visit relatively easily. West German authorities estimate that more
than 5,000 have fled through Hungary since July.
   Hundreds of others refuse to leave West German diplomatic
property in Budapest unless guaranteed safe passage to the West.
Like-minded East Germans are crowding West German embassies,
consulates and missions in East Berlin and Prague, Czechoslovakia.
   Hungary, facing pressure from East Germany, tightened controls
after East Germans massed in groups of as many as 500 and stormed
border points. Authorities in Budapest announced Friday that border
guards would be bolstered by armed units of the Workers' Militia.
   But Hungary is also interested in West German support as it
strives to improve its trading status with West European countries
and seeks convertible currency to modernize its economy.
   Hungarian Foreign Minister Gyula Horn told Hungarian TV late
Saturday his government cannot guarantee East German officials that
all those caught trying to escape through Hungary will be returned
home.
   Horn spoke after returning from Bonn, where he and Hungarian
Premier Miklos Nemeth met with Chancellor Helmut Kohl and Foreign
Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher. Hungary's official news agency MTI
said the talks focused on Hungarian trade ties to the European
Economic Community and on the refugee problem.
   The refugee situation has resulted in months of bad publicity for
East Germany, and Welt am Sonntag said Nemeth told West German
officials that Hungary was under increasing pressure from East
Berlin and Moscow to resolve the problem. The paper did not
elaborate.
   The newspaper said Hungarian officials estimate that about 20,000
of the 200,000 East Germans now vacationing in the country will seek
to flee to the West.
   West German officials have urged East Germany's hard-line
leadership to implement economic and political reforms to help stem
the flow of fleeing East Germans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
