<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     08-27 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This city has gained national pre-eminence
in waste. No, not frivolous spending, but real human waste.
   The Environmental Protection Agency has bestowed the National
Award for Beneficial Reuse of Sludge on Austin.
   Ron Bond, acting director of the city's Wastewater Treatment
Department, said last week: ``It may be sludge to you, but it's our
bread and butter. It's a resource.''
   Through a complicated _ and smelly _ scientific process, Austin
turns its 250 tons of sludge per month into fertilizer for city park
grass and crops that feed cattle.
   The city also turns human waste into compost, which has been
dubbed ``Dillo Dirt'' to entice residents to pay for something they
flushed down the toilet three months ago.
   Bond said Dillo Dirt was selected because ``calling it Human
Doo-Doo wouldn't have been too appetizing.'' Dillo is short for
armadillo, in honor of the critters that proliferate in the Texas
countryside.
   Bond credits engineer Jim Doersam as the person ``most
responsible for the success'' of the Dillo Dirt program.
   Doersam said the EPA award shows Austin has turned a nasty
situation around. For 30 years, the city disposed of its sludge in
large lagoons. By the early part of this decade, Austin was
knee-deep in something, and it wasn't civic pride.
   ``You can only put so much sludge in a pond before it comes back
to haunt you _ which it did,'' he said.
   Doersam, who friends call ``The Sludge Guru,'' says he's thrilled
about the EPA award and thinks the Chamber of Commerce might have
something new to brag about.
   ``This will attract a lot of visitors!'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EATONTOWN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Big Zac,'' weighing in at 4.27 pounds,
pulverized his opponents at the stake and made a New Jersey woman
top manager for a third time in the contest to find the beefiest
tomato.
   Minnie Zaccaria won $1,100 Saturday in the 12th annual New Jersey
Championship Tomato Weigh-In.
   She described winning for a third time as ``overwhelming.''
   ``I really didn't think I was going to win it today,'' Ms.
Zaccaria said. ``It was quite thrilling.''
   Ms. Zaccaria, who also won the contest in 1986 and 1988, earned
$1,000 for finishing first and $100 for having the largest homegrown
tomato in Monmouth County, said contest organizer Joe Heimbold.
   ``She is a fantastic gardener,'' Heimbold said. ``Maybe if she
had left it out on the vine a few more days, maybe it would have
been five pounds.''
</TEXT>
