<FIRST>r a AM-BugEatBug     08-27 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bug Eat Bug,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bugs That Bug Other Bugs Big Biz For California Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VENTURA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's a bug-eat-bug world for Jack Blehm
and son.
   Jack and Jake Blehm breed good insects to eat bad insects at
Rincon Vitova, one of a group of 15 ``insectaria'' nationwide. Every
day, Rincon produces more than 80 million voracious critters from
ladybugs to wasps.
   Business at Rincon Vitova has tripled in the past five years as
farmers concerned about the effects of pesticides are turning to
natural alternatives.
   In 1988 alone, the Blehms say, they supplied millions of dollars
worth of natural predators to customers across three continents.
   The 15 insectaria have sales totaling $25 million annually, the
Blehms estimate.
   Most insects are sold to cotton and vegetable growers, plus back
yard farmers.
   Some colleges and universities are adding classes on integrated
pest management _ ways of holding down troublesome pests while
minimizing the use of pesticides. The Association of Applied Insect
Ecologists, a trade group, is producing a video that shows farmers
how to work with beneficial insects.
   ``This is the future,'' added Ken Hagen, a professor of
entomology at the University of California, Berkeley. ``There is a
great need. The farmers are desperate.''
   State agriculture officials estimate less than 10 percent of the
Golden State's growers use the method. Controlling pests with
beneficial insects takes longer. And because pesticides kill good
bugs along with bad, farmers are forced to stop chemical spraying
while waiting for the good bugs to do their duty.
   ``The hardest thing for the farmer is to have enough faith,''
Jake Blehm said. ``He's not used to seeing pests in the field; he's
used to a quick knockdown.
   ``With this method, you have to watch for several weeks before
you see a difference. And at the beginning, all the farmer sees is
that his crop is contaminated with bugs.''
   Rincon Vitova sells 15 species including beetles, mites and
parasitic wasps that help control flies around chickens and cattle.
   Jack Blehm, a licensed pest control adviser, provided the
business and production expertise. His partner, E.J. Dietrick, an
entomologist formerly with the biological control division at UC
Riverside, provided the field know-how.
   The company employs about 40 workers during peak season from
April to September. The insects are grown in a series of former ship
cargo containers.
   Rincon Vitova even sells bugs to movie makers. Last summer, a
studio filming a horror movie placed a request for four gallons of
maggots. ``We shipped them Federal Express to their location site in
Montana,'' Jake Blehm said.
   More than 600 species of beneficial insects have been introduced
into American agriculture in the past 100 years to curb pest
populations, according to the U.S. Department of Agriculture, which
must approve the insects for use before insectaria start breeding
and releasing them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
