<DOCNO> AP890827-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-89 1529EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Panama     08-27 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama,0775</SECOND>
<HEAD>Noriega Hangs On Despite U.S. Pressure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Panamanian government, which has
resisted every U.S. attempt to oust de facto ruler Manuel Antonio
Noriega, is making new claims that Washington is preparing to invade.
   Foreign Minister Jorge Ritter said Saturday there is a ``true
danger'' of a U.S. invasion to oust Noriega, who heads Panama's
Defense Forces.
   Speaking to reporters, Ritter said the United States has used
military maneuvers allowed under the 1977 Panama Canal Treaties to
shield its preparations.
   ``If all the preliminary steps to an invasion have been taken,
the only thing left is the definitive step,'' he said without
elaborating.
   The United States has been trying to dislodge Noriega for 18
months. It has indicted the general for drug trafficking, slapped
crippling economic sanctions on Panama, and tried to muster
diplomatic support from other Latin American countries.
   ``The U.S. pressures will continue,'' said an embassy official on
condition of anonymity. ``There can be no accommodation with a
regime that includes Noriega.''
   The United States has frozen Panamanian government assets in U.S.
banks and withheld more than $300 million in Panama Canal funds. The
Panamanian government now has trouble meeting payrolls, unemployment
is more than 20 percent, and economic activity has fallen by nearly
a third.
   ``This is a government that survives by lurching from one payday
to the next,'' said one American source.
   In addition, Noriega's domestic opponents have mounted general
strikes and huge demonstrations. International observers say the
opposition beat Noriega's candidate in May presidential elections
that Noriega annuled.
   Despite the pressure, Noriega has remained in power and even
scored some diplomatic victories.
   Last week, the Organization of American States blamed the United
States for the lack of progress in its negotiations on a Sept. 1
change of government. The organization did not even mention Noriega
by name.
   The defiant general survived a March coup and purged the Defense
Forces of disloyal elements. He has wrapped himself in a nationalist
banner and profited from the strong Latin American aversion to
anything that smacks of outside interference _ especially from the
United States.
   On Saturday, the government took the offensive against its
domestic opponents, closing three opposition party newspapers. It
also said it will arrest their editors and confiscate equipment used
to publish them.
   All the papers have called for Noriega's ouster.
   The big question is what the United States will do now.
   According to Noriega, the attempt to oust him is a thinly
disguised plot for the United States to renege on the 1977 treaties
that turn the Panana Canal over to Panama at the end of the century.
   If anything, the 51-year-old general appeared more relaxed than
ever when he showed up for an agricultural fair on a military base
about 80 miles southwest of Panama City last week. Dressed in
civilian clothes, Noriega drank beer with fairgoers and strolled
around, greeting crowds of well-wishers.
   His power base is the Defense Forces, which controls everything
from traffic to city police to customs. It even acts as local
government in many small towns, dispensing municipal largesse such
as roads and other public works projects.
   The 14,000-man Defense Forces is the only armed Panamanian
authority in the country.
   The United States, which has said all options are on the table
when it comes to removing Noriega, has about 12,000 troops in Panama
under the canal treaties. Gen. Marc Cisneros, head of the U.S.
Southern Command, has said he favors military action against Noriega
and he has stepped up the pace of military maneuvers.
   ``We will continue to reaffirm our rights under the terms of the
Canal Treaties and to defend U.S. lives and property and let the
chips fall where they may,'' said U.S. Embassy Deputy Chief of
Mission John Maisto in an interview.
   Several times in the past few months, Panamanian and U.S.
soldiers have pointed weapons at each other, alleging violations of
the treaties.
   ``I would not discount a desperate suicide action by Cisneros
before Sept. 1,'' Defense Forces spokesman Maj. Edgardo Lopez
Grimaldo said in an interview. ``It could be a military invasion or
a terrorist act.''
   The Noriega-controlled government is expected to form a junta to
take over Sept. 1, the date the constitution says a new president
should take office.
   The opposition, in what Noriega called a ``historic stupidity,''
has refused to take part in any junta, demanding Noriega's departure
and recognition that it won the May 7 elections.
</TEXT>
