<FIRST>r i AM-Pakistan-Plane     08-27 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pakistan-Plane,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two British Trekkers May Have Clue To Missing Plane</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two British men hiking in Pakistan's
rugged Karakorum Mountain range spotted a low-flying aircraft near
the area where a passenger plane disappeared, an airline spokeswoman
said Sunday.
   The Pakistan International Airlines twin-engine Fokker-27 with 54
people on board has been missing since early Friday, when it took
off from the northern mountain village of Gilgit for Islamabad, 175
miles south.
   Kevin Edwards and Steven Hall, the trekkers, arrived in Gilgit
early Sunday and told of seeing a low-flying plane near the
26,606-foot Naked Mountain on Friday, said airline spokeswoman Azra
Sultan.
   ``We have been following a lot of leads but this looks the most
promising,'' she said. ``Naked Mountain is the highest mountain in
the Karakorum range. It's the one climbers go out to conquer.''
   The airline's Cpt. Qasim Hyatt said that if weather permits
Monday, helicopters will drop five people, including the two
mountain climbers, on a glacier about 16,000 feet up Naked Mountain.
Aircraft have been scanning the mountain range for the past 72 hours.
   The airline said Paul McGorrian, a freelance jounalist from St.
Petersburg, Fla., was aboard the aircraft, which was carrying 49
passengers and five crew members.
   Airline chairman Daoud Pota told a news conference investigators
have not ruled out sabotage or a hijacking, but he said both appear
unlikely.
   The 27-year-old plane was equipped with an emergency locator
transmitter but it has to be activated manually by survivors. No
signals have been picked up in the area, said Pota.
   None of PIA's fleet of 11 Fokker-27s is equipped with an
automatic locator, he said.
   Deteriorating weather hampered search efforts Sunday. A thick
cloud cover blanketed the valleys of the Karakorum, said airline
spokesman A.H. Sarooqi.
   ``We have seen many a tragedy in this area, both for PIA and the
military,'' he said. Four aircraft _ a Fokker-27, a DC-3 and two
military C-130s _ have crashed in the area since 1963.
   ``It's very treacherous and inhospitable terrain,'' said Pota.
</TEXT>
