<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-BeautyQueen     08-27 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Beauty Queen,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Soviet Beauty Queen Finds The Business is Tough</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's first beauty queen says her
fantasy of being named the country's most beautiful woman has turned
into an ugly nightmare of threats and blackmail by unscrupulous
organizers.
   Organizers of the Miss U.S.S.R. pageant have threatened to strip
her of the title and send another contestant to the Miss World
contest if she doesn't knuckle under to their contract demands,
which 17-year-old Yulia Sukhanova termed ``bondage.''
   ``In three months of torment I have lived through so many
humiliations, disappointments and accusations that I'm simply amazed
I haven't lost my mind,'' Miss Sukhanova, of Moscow, said in a
letter published Sunday in the newspaper Sovietskaya Rossiya.
   Miss Sukhanova said the director of the Venets organization
refused to allow her to bring a chaperone on any travels abroad with
him because he wanted to be alone with her. She also accused him of
blocking business offers from the West from reaching her, and of
sabotaging the one deal she managed to put together herself.
   Miss Sukhanova, who said she wants a career in advertising, was
chosen as the first Miss U.S.S.R. from among 35 contestants by a
panel of judges and by a television audience, which voted by
telephone.
   Before the pageant's final on May 21, the Venets organization
`insisted, by way of threats and blackmail, that the girls sign an
agreement of bondage, limiting their rights and legal
capabilities,'' Miss Sukhanova wrote.
   Some of the contestants refused to sign, but she did, she said.
   However, after she won, Miss Sukhanova and her mother went to
Venets director Yuri S. Kushnerev and said the contract was invalid
because she is a minor.
   They offered to negotiate a new contract under which her mother
and a long-time acquaintance would travel with her until she reaches
18. She accused Kushnerev of rejecting that proposal because he was
interested in making unescorted trips with the pageant contestants.
   Miss Sukhanova accused Kushnerev of blocking any business or
travel proposals from reaching her while he was negotiating in the
United States on her behalf.
   At the same time, she charged, ``he constantly told me and my
family that there was no interest in me among Western agencies, and
that I wouldn't go anywhere at all if I didn't sign the contract
with him.''
   Miss Sukhanova said she did manage to find another outlet to the
West, through the Moscow Cultural Fund, and signed a five-year
agreement with an unidentified American company on July 7.
   She was preparing to leave for the United States on Aug. 13 when
Kushnerev through his lawyer ``openly promised to use all his
contacts all the way to the Communist Party Central Committee to
make sure I would never go anywhere.''
   The Moscow Cultural Fund hastily retreated and the trip to the
United States is off, she said.
   She appealed to the newspaper for help.
   The Soviet Union for decades has frowned on beauty contests as an
example of the West's exploitation of women. But reforms instituted
by President Mikhail S. Gorbachev have opened the way for more
diversity, and that has included the establishment of several beauty
contestants.
</TEXT>
