<SECOND>AM-BRF--Floating Hotel,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Floating Hotel Arrives in Vietnam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HO CHI MINH CITY, Vietnam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $70 million floating luxury
hotel that failed to draw tourists on Australia's Great Barrier Reef
has arrived in Vietnam, where it will reopen on the Saigon River.
   Thousands of residents lined the river Sunday to await the
arrival of the six-story, 200-room hotel, which officials hope will
help Ho Chi Minh City attract foreign businessmen, investors and
tourists.
   But its arrival was delayed until Monday when the 1,700-ton
Saigon Floating Hotel, as it is now called, broke its tow lines soon
after arriving in Saigon River and tug boats had to chase it down.
   The hotel, to open in October, is regarded as a symbol of the
city's re-emerging spirit after the drab years of economic hardship
and tight political control that followed the Communist victory in
1975.
   The Saigon Floating Hotel is the first of several joint ventures
in Vietnam by Ho Chi Minh City, the Japanese hotel and resort
developer EIE International, and Milcon Gulf, a Middle East
investment company.
</TEXT>
