<HEAD>Former President of State Railroad Killed in Ambush</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: 'ndrangheta is cq for name of group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REGGIO DI CALABRIA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attackers on Sunday ambushed and
killed a former president of the state railroad who resigned in a
corruption scandal, and authorities blamed organized crime for the
assassination.
   Investigators said two or three gunmen killed Lodovico Ligato in
the driveway of his seaside home in this provincial capital in
southern Italy.
   Investigators said the killing was apparently the work of the
'ndrangheta, an organized crime group in Calabria. So far this year,
officials say there have been 95 'ndrangheta killings in the
province, including 35 in Reggio Di Calabria, a city of about 90,000
people.
   Chief investigator Federico Strano said it was too early to speak
with certainty about the motive.
   Ligato, 50, was a lawyer, journalist and former Christian
Democratic member of Parliament. He resigned from the state railroad
in November during a bidding scandal in which a $120-million
contract to supply disposable sheets for sleeping berths was
allegedly steered to one company.
   He has denied wrongdoing, but he said in his letter of
resignation that the criminal investigation was one of the reasons
he was resigning.
