<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon     08-27 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Envoy Calls For Syrian Withdrawal</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet envoy on a Lebanese peace mission
has proposed that Syria and Israel both withdraw soldiers from
Lebanon and a presidential election be held, Arab diplomatic sources
said Sunday.
   Envoy Gennady Tarasov has been trying to sell his proposal during
talks in Lebanon, Jordan and Syria, a key Soviet ally, the sources
said.
   His talks represented one of several diplomatic efforts under way
Sunday to end months of fierce fighting between Christians and
Syrian forces.
   On Sunday, Beirut gun battles between Christian army units and
Syrian forces allied with Moslem militias flamed anew. Sixteen
people were reported injured.
   The latest casualties raised the toll to at least 796 killed and
2,247 wounded since the latest round of the 14-year-old civil war
broke out March 8.
   In another development, a radical Iranian newspaper said Pope
John Paul II should not visit Lebanon because he would offend
Moslems. Lebanon's Maronite Catholic leader said such a visit could
prove helpful to Moslems and Catholics.
   Tarasov arrived in Amman, Jordan, on Sunday on the Soviet mission
aimed at a Lebanese truce.
   At the same time, Foreign Minister Farouk Al-Sharaa of Syria
wound up meetings on Lebanon with Jordanian officials.
   Syrian troops in Lebanon, who number about 40,000, were sent
under terms of a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate.
   The Arab diplomatic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Tarasov was seeking a compromise that would allow the Arab
League to reactivate a stalemated peace effort.
   Under his formula, Syrian forces would pull out of Moslem west
Beirut and the central mountains to the Bekaa Valley in east Lebanon
while a presidential election in Lebanon was arranged to end a
year-old political deadlock, the sources reported. Syrian troops
control most of the country outside the Christian sector.
   ``Tarasov is suggesting a compromise under which the Syrian
pullback would be tied to an Israeli pullout from a border enclave
in south Lebanon,'' one source said.
   The Israeli army has occupied a self-declared ``security zone''
in south Lebanon since Israel withdrew most of its forces in
mid-1985, three years after invading Lebanon.
   The diplomatic source said Tarasov has received ``encouraging
responses'' from Christian army commander Michel Aoun and other
involved parties, but that the Soviets will ask the United States to
pressure Israel to agree to the plan.
   Aoun, who has vowed to force the Syrians out of Lebanon, was
named head of an interim cabinet by outgoing President Amin Gemayel
in September. A deadlock between Moslem and Christian politicans
blocked election of a successor by lawmakers.
   Aoun now is vying for power with a Syrian-backed Moslem
government headed by acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss.
   In still another peace effort, King Hussein of Jordan flew into
Cairo, Egypt, on Sunday for an afternoon of talks dealing with
Lebanon and other regional issues. The Egyptian government's Middle
East News Agency said the monarch immediately began meeting with
President Hosni Mubarak.
   The Tehran-based newspaper Jomhuri Islami was quoted as saying if
the pope visits Lebanon, he would be supporting Aoun.
   The Roman Catholic leader said last week he would like to
undertake a peace mission to Lebanon, but no date has been set. The
Vatican has said a final decision will depend on security conditions
in Beirut.
   The French government said it sent its six warships, led by the
aircraft carrier Foch, to evacuate 7,000 French citizens if the
situation worsens.
   In Paris, the navy announced Sunday that a French helicopter
crashed near the Foch during a routine flight and the two crewmen
were missing. It said the cause of Saturday's crash was unknown.
</TEXT>
