<FIRST>u i AM-Angola     08-27 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angolan Rebel Meets South African Leader; Willing to Resume Peace
Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan guerrilla leader Jonas
Savimbi, who canceled a cease-fire in Angola's civil war last week,
softened his stance after talks Sunday with South African leader
F.W. de Klerk.
   Savimbi said his rebel National Union for the Total Independence
of Angola still is committed to peace in Angola and promised he will
attend an African summit to put the fractured peace process back on
track in Zaire next month.
   On Thursday, Savimbi said a 2-month-old cease-fire has failed and
ordered his fighters to resume their 14-year war against Angola's
Marxist government.
   But after meeting de Klerk, Savimbi said in a statement:
   ``We welcome the prospect of resuming talks with the (Angolan
government) at the earliest possible opportunity. (We) commit
ourselves again to the effort to achieve peace and national
reconciliation.''
   The statement did not say the guerrillas will observe the
cease-fire.
   Angola's government and the guerrillas repeatedly have accused
each other of violating the cease-fire and reported heavy fighting
recently.
   Savimbi said the truce and subsequent peace negotiations are
failing because some African leaders misinterpreted a June 22
cease-fire agreement reached in Zaire.
   Zambian President Kenneth Kaunda, present at the Zaire talks and
a related summit in Zimbabwe last week, said Savimbi agreed to go
into temporary exile and that his troops would be integrated into
Angola's existing one-party structure.
   Savimbi says he never agreed to leave, but he would consider
temporary retirement inside the country if he could later contest
open elections.
   The rebels have been at war for a share in government since
Portuguese colonizers hastily withdrew from the country in 1975,
leaving rival groups to fight it out for power. The Popular Movement
for the Liberation of Angola, now led by President Jose Eduardo dos
Santos, won.
   ``The statement issued by President Kaunda ... about the content
of the agreements reached (in Zaire) ... is misleading and
destructive to the prospect of peace and democratic
self-determination in Angola,'' Savimbi said.
   The agreements set general guidelines for ending the Angolan war
but made no mention of Savimbi's future role.
   Savimbi said there were no secret accords and that Kaunda, a
strong supporter of the Angolan government, is attempting to
``redefine history.''
   Kaunda ``has succeeded in doing no more than embarrassing his
friends and risking the fragile peace,'' Savimbi said.
   De Klerk is to meet Kaunda in Zambia on Monday to discuss Angola
and other regional issues. On Friday, de Klerk met in Zaire with
President Mobutu Sese Seko and the two agreed to mediate between the
warring Angolans.
   South Africa supported Savimbi until a regional peace treaty in
December with Angola, which also calls for a phased withdrawal of
Cuba's 50,000 soldiers from Angola.
   Washington supplies the guerrillas with about $15 million in
annual aid.
</TEXT>
