<FIRST>r a AM-SwindallSentencing     08-27 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Swindall Sentencing,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Congressman To Be Sentenced On Perjury Conviction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five years after he won election to Congress,
former U.S. Rep. Pat Swindall goes before a judge Monday for
sentencing on his felony perjury conviction, and most likely will be
sent to prison.
   Swindall, 38, a two-term Republican from Atlanta's eastern
suburbs, was convicted June 20 on nine counts of perjury for lying
to a federal grand jury about his 1987 dealings with an undercover
agent posing as a drug-money launderer.
   He will be sentenced Monday by U.S. District Judge Richard C.
Freeman, who presided over Swindall's trial. Swindall faces between
10 months and five years in prison on each count _ the sentences can
run concurrently _ plus fines of up to $250,000 on each.
   The case falls under federal mandatory sentencing guidelines
which, for his crime, do not include probation. Federal probation
officials, the prosecution and Swindall's attorneys have filed
confidential recommendations with the judge, outlining the sentence
they believe is proper for Swindall under the guidelines.
   Federal probation officials and prosecutors are seeking a prison
sentence of 37 to 46 months, according to published reports.
Swindall's attorneys reportedly are suggesting that the sentencing
guidelines call for 10 to 16 months, and they are seeking a lighter
sentence than that.
   Swindall last week declined to discuss the case, saying he
preferred to wait until after sentencing to make his comments.
   In calling for the stiffer sentence, assistant U.S. attorneys
Craig A. Gillen and Thomas Bever said in a sentencing memorandum
that Swindall's suffering is of his own doing.
   ``While it is true that as a young, multimillionaire congressman
with a seemingly bright political future the defendant's descent
must have been quite painful for him and his family, it is a pain
created by his own hand,'' the prosecutors wrote.
   ``As the defendant emphasizes his status as a former public
official, one is remembered of the edict, `To those whom much is
given, much is expected.' Unlike so many others who have come before
this court for sentencing with limited economic opportunity, limited
intellectual ability and inadequate educational background, the
defendant's horizon was unlimited, bound only by the strength of his
character and moral judgment _ or lack thereof,'' the memo said.
   Swindall's attorneys used a similar argument in seeking a lighter
sentence, saying he should be spared a long prison term because he
lost his House seat, faces permanent expulsion from the state bar
and has suffered enough to ``last a lifetime.''
   Swindall was found guilty of lying to a federal grand jury
investigating a money-laundering sting operation. Evidence in his
trial showed that Swindall repeatedly talked with the undercover
agent and a political associate while he was seeking $850,000 to
finish his luxurious Stone Mountain home, even after a time when he
told the grand jury he had ``walked away'' from the proposed deal.
   Swindall ultimately accepted and endorsed a $150,000 check before
backing out of the deal.
   The jury found Swindall guilty of telling 18 deliberate, willful
lies in his grand jury testimony.
   Swindall was largely unknown politically before he won the 4th
Congressional District seat in 1984, upsetting veteran Democrat
Elliott Levitas. He was re-elected in 1986, but lost the seat in
1988 to Democrat Ben Jones while under the cloud of his perjury
indictment.
   Swindall sought a speedy trial before the 1988 election in hopes
of getting an acquittal and preserving his career, but the trial was
aborted after Swindall campaign mailings, maintaining his innocence,
reached members of the jury.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890827-0034 </DOCNO>
