<FIRST>u i AM-SouthAfrica     08-27 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Use Birdshot On Activists; Four Youths Hurt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAHM VENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police fired birdshot at
anti-apartheid demonstrators Sunday, injuring four teen-age boys in
a mixed-race township outside Cape Town, witnesses said.
   The youths, all aged 16 or 17, were shot shortly after taking
part in a rally to protest Sept. 6 parliamentary elections that
exclude the 28 million black majority, the witnesses said.
   The four were not seriously injured and were treated at a nearby
hospital. Col. J.L. de Vries, the police spokesman on duty, said he
had no information about the incident.
   Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu meanwhile urged anti-apartheid
activists to keep demonstrations peaceful, because ``we must use
methods acceptable to God.''
   ``Don't let us undermine a noble struggle by being provoked into
acts of violence,'' Tutu told about 400 people at St. George's
Church in Athlone, a mixed-race township near Cape Town. ``Our
children will die, people will be detained ... but let the violence
come from the (government) system.''
   Police and demonstrators have clashed almost daily in black and
mixed-race townships around Cape Town since leaders launched a
nationwide mass defiance campaign Aug. 2 against South Africa's
apartheid policy of legal race discrimination.
   Protesters are trying to desegregate hospitals, schools, buses,
beaches and other facilities with non-violent demonstrations.
   Organized protests have been largely peaceful. However, many
spontaneous demonstrations have erupted with youths throwing stones
at police and barricading streets with burning tires.
   Police have banned numerous rallies and detained hundreds of
activists without charge.
   Organizers announced several additional protests this week,
including a Sept. 2 march on Parliament in Cape Town. The organizers
also hinted they may call a massive worker stayaway the day before
and day of the polls.
   In other developments:
   _The country's two largest anti-apartheid labor federations vowed
Sunday to strengthen their opposition to labor laws that limit
workers' rights.
   The Congress of South African Trade Unions, which has over
900,000 members, and the smaller National Council of Trade Unions,
did not specify what actions they plan at the end of two days of
meetings near Johannesburg. In the past, they have organized the
work stoppages.
   _More than 1,000 people attended the funeral of Eric Gumede, the
activist killed four days after his Aug. 12 release from detention
without trial. Gumede helped organize and participated in a hunger
strike by detainees that led to the release of hundreds.
   The green, gold and black flag of the outlawed African National
Congress guerrilla movement was draped over Gumede's coffin before
he was buried in KwaMashu, a township outside the Indian Ocean city
of Durban.
</TEXT>
