<FIRST>u i AM-Mengele     08-27 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mengele,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivors Campaign to Reopen Search for Nazi Criminal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holocaust survivors opened a public hearing
Sunday to challenge experts' findings that Nazi criminal Dr. Joseph
Mengele drowned in Brazil in 1979.
   The three-day hearing before a 10-member tribunal at Yad Vashem
Holocaust Memorial focuses on claims Mengele has been spotted
recently in places ranging from an island off the Portuguese coast
to a dental clinic in Sao Paulo, Brazil.
   The proceedings also follow Jewish protests over a Roman Catholic
convent located at Auschwitz death camp in Poland, where Mengele
worked and where 2.5 million of the 6 million Jewish victims of the
Nazis died.
   Mengele, known as the ``Angel of Death,'' has been accused of
sending 400,000 people to die in gas chambers and of conducting
cruel medical experiments on twins at the camp. This week, German
prosecutors announced they are investigating new evidence suggesting
similar experiments were carried out on retarded children.
   Mengele was declared dead in June 1985 by an international team
of forensic experts who concluded ``within a reasonable scientific
certainty'' that a skeleton exhumed from a cemetery in Embu, near
Sao Paulo, was that of Mengele. Israel never accepted the findings.
   Relatives said Mengele drowned near Sao Paulo on Feb. 7, 1979,
but announced the death only in 1985 during an international
campaign to bring him to trial.
   ``There are claims that Mengele is still alive,'' said Aharon
Simcha, a retired Israeli judge heading the tribunal. ``There is a
feeling, especially among Auschwitz survivors and Mengele's victims,
that not enough is being done to bring him to trial.''
   Among those to testify is American actress Susanne Severeid, who
told reporters she saw a person who fit Mengele's description on
Puerto Santo Island near Portugal in April 1985.
   Ms. Severeid said she traveled to the island with her husband, a
former Dutch resistance fighter, after the Simon Wiesenthal Nazi War
Crimes Research Center was told Mengele might be there. She was to
testify at the hearing Tuesday.
   ``I think the body in Brazil was a hoax,'' added Ms. Severeid,
who starred in the television series ``The Paper Chase.'' ``I saw a
man who fits his profile.''
   Four Holocaust survivors also said a Brazilian dentist, Maria
Helena Bueno de Castro, says she treated Mengele in Sao Paulo about
two months after relatives announced his death. She reportedly said
the man she believed was Mengele called himself Pedro Miller.
   Before the hearing, some Auschwitz survivors held an emotional
burial ceremony for ashes of victims they brought back from a visit
to the camp last week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
