<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-27 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Thunderstorms Move Over Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms Sunday dropped heavy rain and hail as
big as baseballs on Nebraska and Kansas, while hot, humid weather
made things uncomfortable in much of the South.
   In Nebraska, the storms dumped 4 inches of rain in two hours on
Overton and nearly 2\ inches on Bertrand in the same time. Nearly 2
inches fell in Grand Island in the six hours ending at 1 p.m. CDT.
   Baseball-size hail fell south of Belleville, Kan., and
marble-size hail spattered Dorchester, Neb.
   Thunderstorms also dropped small hail and heavy rains on North
Dakota. Scattered showers and thunderstorms fell along the lower
Mississippi Valley, the southern Atlantic Coast and the Texas Coast.
One thunderstorm dumped an inch and a quarter of rain on Savannah,
Ga., in an hour.
   Showers and thunderstorms also fell across New Mexico and eastern
Colorad.
   Hot and humid temperatures continued across much of the Southeast
and south central sections of the nation. Afternoon temperatures
were in the 90s from Florida and the Gulf Coast to the Tennessee
Valley, the lower Mississippi and Missouri valleys, eastern Kansas
and the southern Plains, as well as in the desert Southwest.
   In Paducah, Ky., it was 91 degrees and the humidity was 73
percent, producing a heat index of 110 and making it dangerous for
anyone involved in strenuous outdoor work or play. It was even
stickier in Ozark, Ala., where the heat index was 123.
   The mercury hit a record 97 degrees in Pensacola, Fla., snapping
the old mark set in 1947 by 1 degree.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 52
degrees in Cut Bank, Mont., to 101 degrees in Beeville, Texas. The
low in the lower 48 states was 29 degrees in Truckee, Calif.
   The forecast for Monday called for showers and thunderstorms
stretching from the eastern half of the Gulf Coast and Florida to
the Appalachians, the Tennessee and Ohio Valleys, the Great Lakes
region, the upper and middle Mississippi Valley, much of the
northern Plains and the northern Rockies; scattered showers and
thunderstorms from the central and southern Rockies to parts of the
central Plains.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 80s across much of the
nation, the 70s from Washington state to the northern Rockies and
western North Dakota, as well as the upper Mississippi Valley to the
upper Great Lakes, and from northeast New York to New England; in
the 90s from the southern Atlantic Coast to the Gulf Coast, the
Tennessee Valley, the lower Mississippi and Missouri valleys and the
southern Plains; near 100 degrees in northern and central Texas; and
from 90 and 105 degrees from the desert Southwest to the inland
valleys of California and southern Oregon.
</TEXT>
