<FIRST>u i AM-India-Buddhists     08-27 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Buddhists,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Killed as Police Open Fire on Militant Buddhists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SRINAGAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police opened fire on Buddhists protesting
for greater autonomy in northeastern India on Sunday and at least
three demonstrators were killed, authorities said.
   Hundreds of Buddhists in the mountain town of Leh, 150 miles west
of Srinagar, hurled stones at police who charged the crowd and fired
tear gas to disperse protesters, local government spokesman M.S.
Pandit said.
   ``When this proved ineffective the police opened fire, killing a
young man,'' Pandit said in Srinagar, the capital of Jammu-Kashmir
state.
   A government official in Leh said on condition of anonymity that
two more people died later of gunshot wounds.
   Pandit said 15 people were injured before police started
shooting. He did not say whether others were wounded by gunfire.
   Troops in nearby garrisons were placed on alert and a curfew was
imposed soon after the incident, he said.
   Buddhists make up 85 percent of the 70,000 people in the Ladakh
region, which comprises the Leh and Kargil districts near India's
border with China. They allege discrimination by the
Moslem-dominated local government.
   Moslems are 10 percent of the population and the remaining 5
percent are Sikhs and Hindus.
   For the past 15 years, Buddhists have fought for greater autonomy
in the region, but their protests were non-violent until three
months ago. Since then, there have been frequent clashes between the
two communities.
   Sunday's deaths, however, were the first in the regional struggle.
   Earlier this month, the government advised tourists to avoid Leh,
a Buddhist religious and cultural center, after militants threw
boulders at a tourist motor convoy near the town on Aug. 8. At least
30 Western tourists were injured.
</TEXT>
