<FIRST>u i AM-Taiwan-Expulsions     08-27 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Taiwan-Expulsions,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Expel Taiwan-Born American, Canadian Dissidents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police wielded clubs and fired tear gas
Sunday to arrest an American and a Canadian, both Taiwanese-born
dissidents advocating Taiwan's independence from China. The two were
then deported.
   Police said Robert Tsai of Houston and Leo Yi-shih of Toronto
entered the country illegally. Police refused to say which flight
they left on.
   About 300 policemen surrounded the two men as they were driving
to speak at a seminar organized by a private law foundation in
Taipei.
   Club-wielding policemen used tear gas to disperse their
supporters, pulled Tsai and Leo out of their car, and took the two
directly to the airport.
   About 10 supporters of Tsai and Leo clashed briefly with police.
No injuries were reported.
   Taiwan has barred Tsai and Leo from returning to their native
land, saying they advocate that Taiwan no longer should claim to be
part of China.
   Promoting an independent Taiwan is considered seditious by the
Nationalist government, which fled to Taiwan in 1949 after losing a
civil war to Communist forces on the China mainland. It still claims
to be China's legitimate government. The Beijing government
considers Taiwan a renegade province.
   Tsai and Leo managed to return to Taiwan earlier this month to
attend an annual convention for Taiwanese living abroad.
   Police said they used false names to obtain entry visas, and the
officials ordered the two to leave before Friday or face expulsion.
Tsai and Leo said they would not leave voluntarily and wanted to
fight Taiwan's ``blacklist policy'' by staying.
   Dissidents claim about 1,000 overseas Taiwanese have been
blacklisted and prohibited from returning because they support an
independent Taiwan.
   Tsai is a central committee member of the U.S.-based World United
Formosans for Independence, and Leo is director of the U.S.-based
World Federation of Taiwanese Associations.
</TEXT>
