<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-89 1911EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-ShawMuseum     08-27 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shaw Museum,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Admirers Hope to Turn Shaw's Birthplace Into Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The birthplace of Irish playwright George
Bernard Shaw is up for sale, and his admirers are trying to raise
money to turn the yellow brick rowhouse into a museum.
   Members of the Shaw Birthplace Museum Trust said Sunday they have
had talks with financial backers, whom they would not identify,
about purchasing the eight-room house where Shaw was born in 1856.
   Owners Aida and Eugene Giblin want $222,750 when the house at 33
Synge Street in south Dublin is auctioned next month. But that is
twice what the trust thinks it is worth.
   ``They're looking for quite an unrealistic figure,'' said trust
chairman Nora Lever. ``It's in a very bad state of repair.''
   Ms. Lever said the trust will make an offer for the house, but
``if that is not acceptable then we've had it, that's it, out.''
   Similar properties on the street named after another Irish
dramatist, John Millington Synge, are selling for $81,000 to
$108,000, she said.
   ``With its links to Shaw, the house has got to be worth double
the value of other houses in the street,'' Mrs. Giblin said. ``It's
a disgrace that no state agency would come up with the money. The
house should have been declared a national monument years ago.''
   Ms. Lever also criticized the lack of state funding for the house
Shaw lived in until he was 10 years old.
   The playwright, who died in 1950 at age 94, left the National
Gallery of Ireland one-third of the royalties from his published
work, she noted. The unexpected bequest was swelled by the success
of the 1964 film ``My Fair Lady,'' based on Shaw's ``Pygmalion.''
   Other famous Shaw plays include ``Man and Superman,''``Major
Barbara'' and ``Joan of Arc.''
   Shaw came to London in 1876 where he found fame and fortune as an
art, music and drama critic, playwright, commentator and social
reformer.

</TEXT>
