<FIRST>r a AM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0691 08-27 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0691,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Gets a Hit, But Not a Fish</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 5th graf to CORRECT score; adds new last graf with no fish
caught</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush showed off his old
first baseman's style Sunday, getting one hit in two at-bats and
collecting four putouts in a softball game organized by journalists
and local businessmen.
   A captain and first baseman on Yale's baseball team four decades
ago, Bush tried to live down his collegiate reputation as a
good-field, no-hit player in the two innings he played Sunday on the
side of a rump team of White House staffers against a pickup squad
of reporters, photographers and local residents.
   ``Those who said `good field, no hit,' I think it's a vicious
assault, not only on my baseball ability, but on my character,'' he
quipped.
   Bush joined the game in the second inning with the White House
team behind 7-0. He flied out to short center in his first at-bat
but hit a ground double down the first base line his second time up.
   The White House team rallied behind his play, scoring six runs to
narrow the score to 7-6. But after Bush left to go fishing, the
opposing journalists and businessmen recovered and won the game 9-6.
   Softball was one of four sports activities the vacationing
president devoted his attention to Sunday at his seaside home on
Walker's Point. Wedged between them were two church services that he
attended with his visiting houseguests, evangelist Billy Graham and
his wife.
   Originally, Bush said he was going to have what he called a
``quintathelon'' day of jogging, tennis, softball, golf and boating.
He canceled the golf, saying, ``I have a rendezvous with bluefish,''
although he has yet to catch one despite attempts daily since his
arrival Aug. 16. But he squeezed in a game of horseshoes.
   Bush introduced Graham at the tiny First Congregational Church
and noted that the minister recently returned from Eastern Europe
where he preached to 90,000 people in Budapest.
   He said Graham, like himself on his recent trip to Poland and
Hungary, has seen the ``fascinating change taking place'' as those
countries open their political and economic systems.
   At the first service, where the visit of Bush and his wife
Barbara and the Grahams was not expected, about 40 people were in
attendance in the tiny wooden church.
   Graham spoke briefly after commenting that ``One of the wonderful
things about having the president go to church is you get the press
to go to church.''
   At St. Ann's Episcopal, close to Bush's home, a packed
congregation heard Graham preach a on the prodigal son, belief in
God and other Christian themes.
   Bush, in a jovial mood, then invited the small group of reporters
and photographers who travel in his motorcades to his house to watch
his tennis match.
   Using a nickname he has given himself on the golf course and in
the horseshoe pit, he said he wanted to show reporters ``what Mr.
Smooth is like on the courts.''
   Bush and his partner, son Jeb of Florida, teamed against local
friends Spike Heminway and Andy Holden for a vigorous game of
doubles.
   The president's game, with a strong forehand and quick net play,
was peppered with a steady patter of comments such as, ``Great
return,'' ``Get in, get in'' to the ball, ``Sorry, partner,'' and
``All my fault.''
   When the press group left, the Bushes were losing, 2-3, in the
first set.
   Mrs. Bush wandered out with Billy Graham's wife, Ruth. In a
playful attempt to get back at her husband for his remark in front
of reporters who watched her play last week, she repeated his quip
then: ``It's like watching grass grow.''
   Bush accepted an invitation to a softball tournament later
involving the press corps, White House staff and local community
members before his afternoon game of golf. ``That can be my
quintathelon,'' he said.
   Bush was up early for a two-mile jog with daughter Dorothy
LeBlond, dog Millie, two reporters and a White house staff member.
   Asked outside St. Ann's how the fishing was going, he said he
remains determined to catch one. ``I will guarantee there will be
fish caught,'' he said.
   But the president came home empty-handed again.
