<FIRST>r a AM-Frank-Parade     08-27 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Frank-Parade,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Frank Gets Support as He Marches in Parade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FALL RIVER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Barney Frank received spirited
support as he marched in a parade Sunday, three days after admitting
to a relationship with a male prostitute who may have run a sex ring
out of his apartment.
   The parade in this working-class city 45 miles south of Boston
was part of an event named ``Fall River Celebrates America'' that
drew some 100,000 people over the weekend. On Sunday, the
celebration welcomed a fleet of tall ships to the city's port.
   While there were a few muffled boos, most of the crowd gave Frank
thumbs-up signs and cheered the Democratic congressman from
Massachusetts' 4th District as he moved through the parade route.
   Frank, who has admitted he is homosexual, said Friday that he had
once paid for sex with a male prostitute, and then hired the man,
Steve Gobie, to do household chores and run errands.
   Frank said he had hoped to reform Gobie, a felon on probation,
and wrote letters on Gobie's behalf to a Virginia probation officer.
   But Frank fired him when he became suspicious that Gobie was
selling sex from Frank's Washington apartment while the congressman
was out of town.
