<FIRST>r i AM-MiniBirthday     08-27 0155</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mini Birthday,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands of Mini-Lovers Celebrate Car's 30th Birthday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 22,000 Mini cars pulled into Silverstone
raceway Sunday to celebrate the 30th birthday of the doughty little
auto that has barely changed in three decades.
   The box-like car provided cheap and colorful transport and became
a symbol of the Swinging '60s in its early years. It still attracts
40,000 buyers a year.
   Its manufacturer, Austin Rover, decided to hold a birthday party
with an open invitation to Mini owners worldwide.
   By midafternoon, more than 22,000 Mini drivers had responded to
the call at Silverstone near Towcester, 75 miles northwest of London.
   Among those at the party were Mini enthusiasts from the United
States and Australia and a group of 300 fans from Japan, where sales
this year are expected to exceed 8,000.
   A party of West Germans rented a North Sea ferry to ship their
vehicles across to Britain.
