<DOCNO> AP890827-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-89 2033EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ChicagoCrack     08-27 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicago Crack,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crack Creeps Into Chicago, Police Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crack cocaine, a common problem on the East and
West coasts, is beginning to show up more and more in the Chicago
area where until now it has been a rarity, police say.
   Authorities don't know for sure why crack _ a smokable form of
cocaine also known as rock cocaine _ had been so scarce here, but
one theory is that local drug kingpins kept it out of the area
because they feared it would cut into their profitable trafficking
in powder cocaine and heroin.
   Crack is becoming a law enforcement problem in some of the poorer
southern suburbs, and police fear poor city neighborhoods could be
the next stop for dealers. Crack dealers have invaded other urban
centers by establishing footholds first in outlying communities,
police say.
   ``It's virgin soil,'' said Maywood police Lt. Harold Jenkins.
``Dealers figure they can come here and start their own thing.''
   Los Angeles street gangs have introduced crack, which has been
associated with violence in dozens of cities, into Kansas City, Mo.,
Minneapolis and other cities, and police are checking reports that
those gangs also may be involved in Chicago's suburbs.
   A single dose of crack provides a much more intense high than
snorting powder cocaine and costs less, making it popular in poorer
communities and among the young.
   For years, Chicago police have focused their drug activities on
powder cocaine and heroin abuse. While other cities reeled under
soaring homicide rates due to crack, Chicago's homicide rate dropped
to its lowest level in 20 years in 1988.
   Officials say the full extent of crack abuse in Chicago has not
been determined. In a four-month period ending in June, police
raided 20 crack houses, said Sgt. Jim Brady.
   In suburban Harvey, 539 drug arrests were made last year and
police say 95 percent of the narcotics trade there involves crack.
</TEXT>
