<FIRST>u i AM-Cambodia     08-27 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Final Session To Open Amid Fears Conference Falls Short Of Goals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The final session of an international conference to
negotiate peace in Cambodia opens Monday, but lack of progress is to
keep some key foreign ministers away.
   Protagonists at the monthlong conference of 19 nations remained
apart on all major issues, delegates said Sunday, with the role of
the Khmer Rouge _ whose bloody 1975-1978 rule cost at least one
million lives _ at the center of debate.
   Surprise concessions in the final three days were considered
unlikely.
   In Beijing, the official Xinhua news agency reported that Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen of China, a crucial player, would attend the
closing ministerial session only ``if the four committees of the
conference can succeed in producing agreements.''
   China sponsors the Khmer Rouge, the strongest of the three
resistance movements fighting Cambodia's Vietnamese-backed
government.
   It remained unclear Sunday whether Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze would attend. The U.S. State Department announced
Friday that Secretary of State James A. Baker III would not come
because a comprehensive settlement was not in sight.
   It was uncertain whether resistance leader Prince Norodom
Sihanouk would head his delegation.
   In a surprise move, Sihanouk announced he was resigning as
president of his movement, one of three parties within the
resistance, party sources said Sunday. But he remained head of the
resistance and was considering changing his mind, the sources said
on condition of anonymity.
   Dissension between moderates pressing for a negotiated settlement
and others opting to continue the guerrilla war against the
Vietnamese-backed government of Cambodian Prime Minister Hun Sen
prompted Sihanouk's move, the sources said.
   Sihanouk named his wife, Monique, and Gen. Nhiek Tioulong to
replace him as co-presidents of the movement and designated his son,
Prince Ranariddh as secretary-general.
   The conference has sought an overall peace settlement to end two
decades of violence in Cambodia.
   However, Sihanouk's coalition and Hun Sen remain deadlocked on a
formula for sharing power before general elections.
   Sihanouk has insisted the Khmer Rouge be given a role in a
transitional government to rule after the withdrawal of Vietnamese
troops by late September. Hun Sen says the Khmer Rouge must be
``eliminated'' politically and militarily.
   There was speculation the conference could lead to further
negotiations, even another conference, at a later date, and no one
was prepared to predict failure.
   ``We hope by the end of the year there will possibly be
something,'' said Ek Sereywath, a spokesman for Sihanouk's
delegation. He said he could not predict the outcome of the
conference and was hoping for ``a surprise.''
</TEXT>
