<FIRST>r i AM-Spain-Drugs     08-27 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spain-Drugs,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than 400 Arrested In Anti-Drug Operation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spanish police arrested more than 400 people
and seized drugs, guns and jewelry in a 48-hour crackdown on
small-time drug pushers and criminals that ended early Sunday.
   More than 4,000 policemen took part in the operation that covered
Catalonia in the northeast to Andalusia in the south, including the
Balearic and Canary Islands.
   Police seized more than 2 pounds of heroin, 22 pounds of cocaine
and 1,430 pounds of hashish. They also confiscated 25 guns, 75
knives and $132,200.
   Stolen property seized included 100 pieces of jewelry, 50
cameras, 50 radio-cassette players, 30 video cassette recorders and
televisions, and 40 stolen cars, police said.
   On April 23, police seized 1,230 pounds of cocaine on a beach
near Barcelona, and arrested four people. Police said the seizure
was the largest ever in Europe.
   Spain has become a major point of entry to Europe for cocaine
from Latin America and heroin from the Middle East and Southeast
Asia, drug enforcement agents have said.
