<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0658 08-27 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0658,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Deports Five Palestinians</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th pvs, `Aruri's wife...' to UPDATE with
arrival in Paris. SUBS one graf for 14-15 pvs, `Aruri has...' to UPDATE
with Lebanon arrival; pickup 16th pvs, `Sunday's air...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel on Sunday deported a prominent Arab
activist and four other Palestinians it accused of leading the
uprising against Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The deportations raised to 60 the number of Palestinians expelled
from the occupied territories during the 20-month uprising against
Israeli rule.
   Four Palestinians were deported to Lebanon. A fifth, physicist
Taysir Aruri, whose cause has been championed by international human
rights groups, was expelled to France after he appealed to Israel's
Supreme Court, saying he could face death in Lebanon.
   The deportations came as Israel bombed a pro-Iranian Shiite
stronghold in southeast Lebanon, killing one guerrilla and wounding
five others, police reported. It was the ninth Israeli air raid into
Lebanon this year.
   Aruri's wife brought their three young children to Ben Gurion
Airport to see their father off. But she was removed by police after
she became the center of a scuffle involving pro-Palestinian
demonstrators and angry Israelis.
   Aruri did not speak to reporters when he arrived in Paris. There
has been speculation he was headed for Tunis, headquarters of the
Palestine Liberation Organization. But late Sunday, PLO sources said
he could be planning to go to the United States.
   Aruri has held meetings with Israeli peace activists. He
advocates peaceful creation of a Palestinian state alongside Israel.
   Army Chief of Staff Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron said on army radio
Sunday that Israel would continue to deport Palestinians despite
complaints by foreign governments and human rights groups that the
action violates international law.
   Shomron said Israel considers deportation an effective deterrent
against the uprising.
   The French Foreign Ministry issued a statement saying Aruri was
welcome indefinitely in France, and referred to his expulsion as ``a
measure contrary to the Geneva Convention protecting civilians in
time of war.''
   The United States also has condemned such expulsions as a
violation of the Fourth Geneva Convention.
   None of the five Palestinians expelled Sunday faced trial or
formal charges. Appeals by four of the men were rejected by the
Supreme Court Thursday, and the fifth was turned down a month
earlier. The court never has overturned an army deportation order.
   Aruri, 43, a physics professor at the West Bank's Bir Zeit
University named a ``prisoner of conscience'' by Amnesty
International, was accused of being a member of the outlawed
Palestinian Communist Party.
   The army also said he was ``involved in planning the uprising and
a member of the uprising's unified command.'' The announcement of
the four other deportations said the men ``participated in leading
and directing the uprising'' in the West Bank.
   One deportee, Mohammed Matur, was accused by the army of being a
leader of PLO chief Yasser Arafat's mainstream Fatah faction. The
others were said to be members of the Marxist Democratic Front for
the Liberation of Palestine, a leftist PLO group.
   On arrival in south Lebanon, Lebanese police reported the four
asked to be taken to bases of the Democratic Front in western Bekaa
valley.
   Sunday's air raid into Lebanon was believed to be in retaliation
for the Aug. 9 suicide car bomb attack carried out by the
Iranian-supported Hezbollah. Five Israeli soldiers and an allied
Lebanese militiaman were injured in the car bombing, and Israeli
officials have vowed to avenge the attack.
   Hezbollah, or the Party of God, has said it carried out the
bombing to avenge Israel's kidnapping of a Shiite Moslem cleric,
Sheik Abdul-Karim Obeid. Israeli commandos seized Obeid in a
southern Lebanese village on July 28.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
