<HEAD>Mechanic Loses Leg Crushed by Taxiing Jet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 22-year-old airline mechanic lost her lower
right leg after she was run over by a taxiing jet at O'Hare
International Airport, her surgeon said Sunday.
   Hope Lewellen, 22, of Orland Park was in critical but stable
condition at Lutheran General Hospital in suburban Park Ridge after
nine hours of surgery to repair injuries to both legs suffered
Saturday, said Dr. Wayne Goldstein.
   Ms. Lewellen, a Continental Airlines employee, had been directing
a Scandinavian Airlines 767 jet to a gate for departure to
Stockholm, Sweden, when she was run over.
   Ms. Lewellen leaned down to pick up earphones that had fallen off
her head, and the pilot did not know she was still behind the
aircraft, which was backing up, said Patrolman Dan Cirighini of the
police department's O'Hare unit.
   Continental employees were the only people aboard the plane at
the time, said airline spokeswoman Marj Abrams. Continental is under
contract with Scandinavian Airlines to service Scandinavian's jets
in the United States.
