<FIRST>r a AM-RacialAttack 1stLd-Writethru a0706 08-27 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Racial Attack, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0706,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whites Taunt Marchers Protesting Killing of Black Youth</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Trims lead; SUBS 5th graf, `Some residents ...,' to ADD that
some in crowd made obscene gestures; SUBS 16th graf, `Five suspects ...,'
to UPDATE with five released on bail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS F. McELROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of whites in a Brooklyn community where a
black teen-ager was slain angrily taunted about 100 people who
marched through the streets Sunday to protest the death.
   The protesters, led by clergy members, gathered in the
Bensonhurst neighborhood where 16-year-old Yusef Hawkins was shot
dead Wednesday as he was confronted by a gang of bat-wielding whites.
   The group of about 30 blacks and 70 whites was escorted by 20
police on motorcycles and dozens more on foot as about 300 white
residents lined the street.
   Many residents watched passively from windows and storefronts
while others walked along the street waving posters in the air and
chanting, ``Go home. Go home.''
   Some residents shouted, ``Free the boys from Bensonhurst,'' a
reference to five white youths who have been arrested in the
slaying. Others booed the marchers and chanted ``Central Park,
Central Park,'' referring to the recent rape and beating of a white
jogger there, allegedly by a gang of blacks and Hispanics. Some made
obscene gestures.
   One man was taken into custody but not immediately charged after
a small firecracker was thrown at the demonstrators, said Sgt. Ed
Burns, a police spokesman.
   The protesters, led by the Rev. Timothy Mitchell, chanted,
``Whose city? Our city,'' as they walked about 10 blocks from the
site of the killing through the community's streets.
   ``New York City is not going to become Johannesburg, South
Africa. This is our city and we are going to walk wherever we want.
We need to see more of the good people in this community,'' Mitchell
said at the site of Hawkins' death.
   Throughout the march, police blocked streets with barricades to
prevent confrontations.
   Hawkins and three friends were attacked by a gang of neighborhood
whites carrying baseball bats, two-by-fours and golf clubs when they
arrived in Brooklyn's mostly Italian-Jewish Bensonhurst section to
answer an advertisement for a used car.
   Police said the gang was angered by a local white girl's dating
of a black youth, and they gathered with the intention of attacking
the black when he arrived for the girl's birthday party.
   A protest march Saturday afternoon by blacks through the mostly
white neighborhood was greeted with jeers, spitting and racial
slurs. Some whites held up watermelons as 300 or so blacks marched
through.
   Residents also chanted ``Central Park, Central Park'' during that
incident. The blacks answered with ``Howard Beach, Howard Beach,'' a
reference to the December 1986 killing of Michael Griffith, 23.
   ``This is about what we expected,'' said Joseph Calzerano, the
police department's chief of operations. ``The feelings are running
high.''
   ``If we didn't do it because of what happened yesterday then it
would be just like South Africa,'' Mitchell said before a brief
memorial service at the site of the killing Sunday.
   Five suspects in the attack were arraigned Saturday. Four were
released Sunday on $75,000 bail; the fifth, Keith Mondello, 18, whom
authorities called the instigator, was released on $100,000 bail.
   The other suspects are Steven Curreri, 18; Pasquale Raucci, 19;
Charles Stressler, 21; and James Patino, 24.
   Meanwhile, police continued looking for 18-year-old Joseph Fama,
who was wanted for questioning. News reports have said investigators
believe he was the gunman.
   Mondello, Curreri, Raucci and Stressler are charged with assault,
aggravated harassment, violation of civil rights, menacing and
possession of deadly weapons, the baseball bats. Patino was charged
with assault, riot, aggravated harassment and violation of civil
rights.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
