<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-89 2326EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Diamond-Star-Union     08-27 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Diamond-Star-Union,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAW Employees at Chrysler-Mitsubishi Venture Ratifiy New Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORMAL, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Auto Workers members at Diamond-Star
Motors, a Chrysler-Mitsubishi joint venture, ratified a three-year
contract Sunday that provides wage-and-benefit increases of more
than 30 percent.
   The new contract, approved by 1,644 of about 2,300 production and
maintenance workers at the auto assembly plant, was worked out
during five months of negotiations.
   The vote was 1,258 in favor to 383 against, said UAW spokesman
Dennis Miller.
   The $650 million plant, which began making cars about a year ago,
employs about 2,900 people. The company produces a two-door sporty
sedan marketed as the Plymouth Laser and the Mitsubishi Eclipse.
   ``We are gratified that the members recognized significant
advances in the first contract and are confident that it builds a
firm foundation for future progress,'' said Bill Stewart, director
of the Chicago-based UAW chapter.
   Under the agreement, production workers who have been on the job
18 months will have a base wage of $12.79 an hour, which will
increase to $17.01 an hour at the end of the three-year contract.
   Maintenance workers, including skilled positions such as
electricians and welders, would begin at $14.89 an hour and increase
to $19.49 at the end of three years.
   The increases include periodic wage increases and cost-of-living
adjustments.
   The raises are intended to bring Diamond-Star workers into line
with the wages of other UAW-represented auto plants, and
specifically with Chrysler plants.
   The contract also includes a ``me too'' provision that passes on
to Diamond-Star workers any Chrysler increases that occur during the
life of the pact.
   Also included is a $750 settlement bonus for ratification of the
contract, and two lump sum payments equal to 3 percent of earnings.
   Job security provisions are ``among the strongest in the
industry,'' according to a letter to members of UAW Local 2488 from
Bill Stewart, regional director.
   According to the contract, the company agrees not to lay off
workers ``unless compelled to do so by severe economic conditions
that threaten the long-term life of the company.''
   If layoffs are necessary, the contract provides that workers
would receive 80 percent of their pay for up to a year. Stewart
termed that part of the contract proposal ``prededent-setting.''
   The agreement also includes added health benefits, retirement at
age 55 after five years of service and other improvements.
</TEXT>
