<FIRST>r a AM-ChildSnipers     08-27 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Snipers,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Juveniles Charged With Shooting At Interstate Motorists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEMPLE HILLS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four children ranging in age from 9 to
14 were apprehended for allegedly firing .22 caliber rifles at
passing motorists on Interstate 95, wounding one person, police said
Sunday.
   The youngsters were captured about 8:30 p.m. Saturday after a
citizen reported gunfire coming from a wooded area near the highway
and police sent up a helicopter to investigate, state police
spokesman Chuck Jackson said.
   The shootings apparently began Aug. 18, when a 49-year-old
Calvert County man was wounded in the shoulder while driving north
on I-95, Jackson said.
   A 14-year-old La Plata youth and an 11-year-old from Temple Hills
were charged with assault with intent to maim. The 14-year-old also
was charged with two counts of assault with intent to murder and one
count of destruction of property, Jackson said.
   Police believe the 14-year-old fired his weapon in the direction
of the state police as they scoured the woods and as the helicopter
circled above, Jackson said.
   The 9-year-old and his 12-year-old brother, both of Temple Hills,
were released into the custody of their parents without being
charged.
   On Aug. 18, James Orchard of Lusby, Md., was injured when a
bullet pierced his windshield and hit his shoulder.
   State police also confirmed at least three other incidents of
gunfire, which resulted in damage to three vehicles on I-95, Jackson
said.
   The 14-year-old was placed in the custody of the Maryland
Department of Juvenile Services. The 11-year-old was released to his
parents' custody.
   Two .22 caliber rifles were recovered in the area where the
youngsters were taken into custody, Jackson said.
</TEXT>
