<FIRST>r f AM-EasternSafety     08-27 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern Safety,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>FAA: Strike Has Not Affected Eastern Safety</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration has
determined that the strike by Eastern Airlines pilots, flight
attendants and Machinists union members has not affected safety.
   ``Eastern's post-strike maintenance compares favorably with that
of air carriers having equivalent aircraft, fleet size, utilization
rates and operating environments,'' the FAA said in a report,
according to The New York Times.
   David I. Shapiro, a court-appointed examiner reviewing Eastern's
Chapter 11 bankruptcy filing protection, requested the FAA report,
the Times reported in Saturday's editions.
   The FAA also gave a passing grade to the replacement pilots
Eastern hired and praised the airline's improved training
procedures, the Times reported.
   ``We've really been raked over the coals by the unions. ... It's
gratifying that the FAA says it's satisfied,'' said Edward F. Upton,
Eastern vice president for maintenance and engineering. Eastern is
owned by Texas Air Corp., which is headed by Frank Lorenzo.
   Officials at the unions, which went on strike March 4, dismissed
the FAA report and questioned the integrity of the investigators.
   The FAA investigators ``see no evil, hear no evil and speak no
evil of Lorenzo and the Texas Air management,'' said Donald L.
Miller, shop committee chairman in Miami for the International
Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers.
</TEXT>
