<SECOND>BC-GM-Brakes,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: GM Plans To Make Antilock Brakes Standard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Antilock brakes will be standard equipment on all
General Motors Corp. cars and light trucks by 1994, according to a
report to be published Monday by an automotive trade journal.
   Over the next three years, GM also plans to offer antilock brakes
as optional equipment on smaller cars, reports the weekly Automotive
Electronic News.
   Some larger GM cars already carry antilock brakes as standard
equipment, while others offer them as extra-cost options.
   GM spokesman Dave Sloan would not confirm the 1994 date, which
the trade journal attributed to unidentified sources.
   ``We have said in public before that we do plan to have antilock
brakes on most of our cars by the mid-1990s,'' Sloan said.
   Antilock brakes help prevent skidding on slippery roads or during
panic stops by varying braking pressure many times a second.
