<FIRST>r f BC-Chrysler-Minivans     08-27 0131</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Chrysler-Minivans,0137</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Agree to Open Talks on Boosting Minivan Output</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp.'s hourly workers at its St. Louis
II assembly plant have voted 1,133-598 to open talks on a new
staffing system that would allow the company to boost output of its
popular stretch minivans.
   Voting concluded Friday, said Billy Joe Jenkins of the United
Auto Workers union Local 110 at the plant.
   Under the proposed staffing system, three crews would be assigned
to staggered shifts of four 10-hour days each. Jenkins said tough
negotiations are ahead, especially if the company resists paying
overtime for Saturday work.
   If approved, the plan would add 1,200 workers to the plant's
3,300 employees and boost vehicle output by about 18 percent without
increasing assembly line speed, Chrysler said.
