<DOCNO> AP890827-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-27-89 1927EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-China-Economy     08-27 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Economy,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Announces New Screening, Closures of Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese authorities announced Sunday a new wave of
closures of commercial, financial and supply companies as part of
their efforts to restore central economic controls that were relaxed
in recent years.
   An order issued by the Communist Party Central Committee and the
State Council, China's cabinet, said elimination of companies that
are ``redundant, not qualified, not able to meet the public needs,
in violation of state laws or disciplines, poorly managed or
insolvent'' will last until March.
   The official Xinhua News Agency announced the decision Sunday but
said it was made Aug. 17, the first indication that the ruling
party's powerful Central Committee met then. There was no
explanation for the delay in announcing the decision.
   Xinhua gave no estimate of the number of companies that would be
closed. It said others would lose preferential treatment, such as
tax reduction or exemption _ favors given by some locales to
encourage new private or semi-private business.
   The government already has said it will cut sharply the number of
companies authorized to conduct foreign trade on the grounds that
the proliferation of trade companies in the past few years has
caused market confusion.
   Last month, the party Politburo and State Council shut down two
large, state-owned conglomerates, including one linked to senior
leader Deng Xiaoping's son, Deng Pufang, and ordered audits of
others. In those cases, however, the main reason given was alleged
corruption.
   The two bodies also barred children and spouses of top government
and party leaders from working in commercial companies because of
frequent conflicts of interest. The government said Saturday that
all those affected by the order had quit their jobs.
   The new order was much broader and appeared directed at the
millions of factories and commercial companies that have sprung up
outside the state plan during a decade of economic reform.
   Central authorities have been trying since last fall to regain
control over these companies, of which some fall under provincial or
city governments and others are privately or collectively owned.
   These operations have far outstripped the large,
central-government controlled sector in efficiency and profits, and
have siphoned away scarce raw materials and funds.
   Many local governments so far have defied Beijing's orders to
``rectify'' their economies, and it was not clear how the government
intended to enforce the new order. Xinhua said provincial governors
would share responsiblity for its implementation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
